1850. Who Controls the Hunt? examines how Ontario’s emerging wildlife conservation laws failed to reconcile First Nations treaty rights and the power of the state. David Calverley traces the political and legal arguments prompted by the interplay of treaty rights, provincial and dominion government interests, and the corporate concerns of the Hudson’s Bay Company. A nuanced examination of Indigenous resource issues, the themes of this book remain germane to questions about who controls the hunt in Canada today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGame lawszOntarioxHistory. 0aOjibwa IndiansxHuntingzOntarioxHistory. 0aOjibwa IndiansxLegal status, laws, etczOntarioxHistory. 0aOjibwa IndiansxLegal status, laws, etc.zOntarioxHistory. 0aOjibwa IndianszOntarioxGovernment relationsxHistory. 0aWildlife conservationxLaw and legislationzOntarioxHistory. 0aWildlife conservationzOntarioxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aWynn, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483135240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774831352423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774831352/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles